[32m+[m[32m                    RULE ONE[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m Trick Your Brain[m
[32m+[m[32mwith the 20 minute[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m         Rule[m
[32m+[m[32m                                                                               www.appbrewery.com[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mLearning to code is a bit like[m
[32m+[m[32m        going to the gym.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mEven if you max out and spend a whole weekend at the[m
[32m+[m[32mgym, you will not see a visible difference in your body. The[m
[32m+[m[32mmore regularly you learn to code, the more likely it is that[m
[32m+[m[32myou‚Äôll start seeing your ripped coding muscles. Ì†ΩÌ≤™ (The[m
[32m+[m[32mirony is not lost on me).[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mBut the problem is where do you find the time? Between[m
[32m+[m[32mworking your full-time job, spending time with your family[m
[32m+[m[32mand life admin, when are you supposed to sit down and[m
[32m+[m[32mpractice this ‚Äúdaily coding‚Äù?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhile I was working as a doctor, I spent about 12 hours at[m
[32m+[m[32mthe hospital, 1-hour commuting and approximately 2 hours[m
[32m+[m[32mon general life-sustaining stuff, such as eating. So that left[m
[32m+[m[32mme with only 9 hours remaining in my day. Theoretically, 2[m
[32m+[m[32mhours could be allocated to coding practice and 7 hours on[m
[32m+[m[32msleep. But there is nothing more difficult than trying to[m
[32m+[m[32mconvince your work-saturated brain to sit down and learn[m
[32m+[m[32mwhen you could be watching Game of Thrones with a tub of[m
[32m+[m[32mice cream.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mCopyright ¬© The App Brewery                                                                        4[m
[32m+[m[32m                             www.appbrewery.com[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mLBeuat thrennI fionundga to trick. code is a bit like[m
[32m+[m[32m going to the gym. As humans, we have a lot of inertia. This can be bad for us -[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   I‚Äôm looking at you, ‚Äú24‚Äù box set. However, we can also turn[m
[32m+[m[32m   it to our advantage. I found that once I started coding and[m
[32m+[m[32m   making things, I got so absorbed into the project that I no[m
[32m+[m[32m   longer cared about TV, food or sleep. There were quite a[m
[32m+[m[32m   few weekends when I coded until sunrise.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   So how do we take advantage of this inertia?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   First, you must understand that task-switching is very[m
[32m+[m[32m   difficult. It requires a lot of motivation. If as soon as you[m
[32m+[m[32m   get home, you slump on the sofa and switch on the TV,[m
[32m+[m[32m   you‚Äôve already lost that evening. This is because the[m
[32m+[m[32m   amount of motivation required to task-switch and do[m
[32m+[m[32m   something not driven by evolution like eating or sleeping is[m
[32m+[m[32m   a Herculean task.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   This is why the moment you enter the door and change to a[m
[32m+[m[32m   new environment is the most crucial. If at this moment,[m
[32m+[m[32m   you tell yourself that you are just going to do 20 minutes of[m
[32m+[m[32m   coding practice, you will most likely succeed and use your[m
[32m+[m[32m   inertia to end up learning for an hour or more. No brain[m
[32m+[m[32m   will perceive a 20-minute task as a lot of effort and you end[m
[32m+[m[32m   up tricking your brain to take advantage of your evening.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mCopyright ¬© The App Brewery                                                       5[m
[32m+[m[32m                                                                               www.appbrewery.com[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mLearning to code is a bit like The next step is to develop a habit. Research suggests that[m
[32m+[m[32m   to develop a new habit, you have to carry out the task daily[m
[32m+[m[32m going to the gym. for a month. I‚Äôve used this next trick for loads of different[m
[32m+[m[32m   things, from exercising to coding, it invariably works like a[m
[32m+[m[32m   charm. To preface this trick, I want you to imagine a wall[m
[32m+[m[32m   with five paintings hanging on it, four of which are[m
[32m+[m[32m   perfectly aligned, perfectly horizontal, but one is crooked.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   Now really imagine it, is there a part of you that wants to[m
[32m+[m[32m   fix it?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   Now let‚Äôs imagine a monthly calendar with boxes[m
[32m+[m[32m   representing individual days. If you nurture that new habit[m
[32m+[m[32m   on a particular day, then you make a line through that day.[m
[32m+[m[32m   If you continue your streak the next day then you extend[m
[32m+[m[32m   that line and so forth. There is something about not[m
[32m+[m[32m   breaking a continuous line that motivates most people to[m
[32m+[m[32m   continue to develop a habit. As strange as it sounds, there[m
[32m+[m[32m   are many times when I would have given up, but was[m
[32m+[m[32m   compelled to continue because of a long, continuous line.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mCopyright ¬© The App Brewery                                                                        6[m
[32m+[m[32m      2[m
